The '''Ana people,''' also known as the '''[[Atakpame]] people,''' are an ethnic group of [[Benin]] and [[Togo]]. The Ana are concentrated between Atakpame, primarily in the Gnagna and Djama quarters, as well as between Atakpame and [[Sokode]] and down to the Togo-Benin border. Ethnologists identify the Ana as the most western of the [[Yoruba people|Yoruba]] subgroups. In fact, the Ana trace their origins to [[Ife]], and their dialect is also called [[Ifè language|Ife]], which has about 210,000 speakers.<Ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=MdaAdBC-_S4C&pg=PA28&lpg=PA28&dq=Ana+Yoruba+in+Atakpame#v=onepage&q=Ana%20Yoruba%20in%20Atakpame&f=false|title=The Peoples of Africa: An Ethnohistorical Dictionary (ABC-Clio ebook)|author=James Stuart Olson|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|year=1996|isbn=9780313279188}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author1=Appiah, Kwame Anthony|author2=Henry Louis Gates, Jr.|title=''Africana,''|edition=1st|location=New York|publisher=Basic Civitas Books|isbn=0-465-00071-1}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Uk1Tbdsq99gC&pg=PA133&dq=Ana+Yoruba#v=onepage&q=Ana%20Yoruba&f=false|title=	The Yoruba Diaspora in the Atlantic World (Blacks in the Diaspora)|page=133|author1=Toyin Falola|author2=Matt D. Childs|publisher=Indiana University Press|year=2005|isbn=9780253003010}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=D2N5PKqtjs0C&pg=PA13&lpg=PA13&dq=Ana+Yoruba+in+Atakpame#v=onepage&q=Ana%20Yoruba%20in%20Atakpame&f=false|title=African Dilemma Tales (bascom) World anthropology|issn=1572-6339|author=William Russell Bascom|publisher=Walter de Gruyter|year=1975|isbn=9789027975096|page=13}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.punchng.com/in-togo-atakpame-keeps-yoruba-language-alive/|title=In Togo, Atakpame keeps Yoruba language alive|date=December 30, 2015|accessdate=December 30, 2015|publisher=The Punch}}</ref>

